Health Minister Aaron Motsoaledi has on Tuesday announced that at least 30 people have died after listeriosis outbreak in South Africa. Motsoaledi indicated that a total of 557 laboratory-confirmed listeriosis cases which were reported from all provinces. “Most cases were reported from Gauteng Province (62%, 345/557) followed by Western Cape (13%, 71/557) and KwaZulu-Natal (7%, 37/557).” In July, doctors from neonatal units in the Chris Hani Baragwanath and Steve Biko hospitals alerted the National Institute for Communicable Disease (NICD) about unusually high numbers of babies with listeriosis. Motsoaledi said the source of the listeriosis outbreak is currently being investigated and that all stakeholders are cooperating with the investigation led by the NICD. Listeriosis is a foodborne illness which is associated with a wide variety of foods, including dairy products, meat products, vegetables, fruit, and ready-to-eat products. “Those at high risk of developing severe disease include newborns, the elderly, pregnant women, persons with weak immunity such as HIV, Diabetes, Cancer, Chronic liver or Kidney disease,” Motsoaledi said. Motsoaledi urged all South Africans to wash their hands before handling food and often during food preparation. “Keep food at safe temperatures. Food to be kept cold should be refrigerated and food to be served hot should be served hot.” -TNA Reporter  